addr="alex-nelson"
title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>The claim is that this forms a Jordan algebra. We need to verify that Jordan product satisfies both axioms (commutativity and the Jordan identity).</fr:p>

<fr:p>We observe this product is commutative since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[AB+BA=BA+AB]]></fr:tex> (thanks to the commutativity of addition) and furthermore it is linear in the first slot (therefore bilinear, i.e., it distributes over addition).</fr:p>

<fr:p>Let us now verify the Jordan product satisfies the Jordan identity.</fr:p>

<fr:p>We see that:</fr:p>

<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\begin {align*} 8(A\circ  B)\circ (A\circ  A) &= 2(AB+BA)\circ (A^{2}+A^{2})\\ &= 2(AB+BA)A^{2} + 4A^{2}(AB+BA)\\ &= 2ABA^{2}+2BA^{3}+2A^{3}B+2A^{2}B \end {align*}]]></fr:tex>

<fr:p>and</fr:p>

<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\begin {align*} 8A\circ (B\circ (A\circ  A)) &= 4A\circ (BA^{2}+A^{2}B)\\ &= 2A(BA^{2}+A^{2}B)+2(BA^{2}+A^{2}B)A\\ &= 2ABA^{2} + 2A^{3}B + 2BA^{3} + 2A^{2}B \end {align*}]]></fr:tex>

<fr:p>We see that these two are equal to each other, therefore satisfies the Jordan identity. Hence it is a Jordan algebra.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
